"modebar-btn" data-title="Show closest data on hover" data-attr="hovermode" data-val="closest" data-toggle="false" data-gravity="ne"><svg viewBox="0 0 1500 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m375 725l0 0-375-375 375-374 0-1 1125 0 0 750-1125 0z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a><a rel="tooltip" class="modebar-btn active" data-title="Compare data on hover" data-attr="hovermode" data-val="x" data-toggle="false" data-gravity="ne"><svg viewBox="0 0 1125 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m187 786l0 2-187-188 188-187 0 0 937 0 0 373-938 0z m0-499l0 1-187-188 188-188 0 0 937 0 0 376-938-1z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a></div></div></div><svg class="main-svg" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="563.3333333333334" height="508.33333333333337"><g class="hoverlayer"></g></svg></div></div></div></foreignObject></g><g transform="translate(644,56)" x="644" y="56" title="codeHTML" width="475" height="539" class="codeHTML" name="codeHTML" rot="0"><foreignObject x="0" y="0" width="222" height="200" style="height: 539px; width: 791.667px;"><div name="htmlCode" style="zoom: 60%; height: 539px; width: 791.667px;" code="<div class=&quot;ch&quot;>
    
    <h1>Chaotic Oscillator Circuit - SPICE Time Domain Analysis</h1>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot;>
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Transistors (Q1, Q2):</strong> BC549C NPN</li>
            <li><strong>Resistors:</strong> R1=5kΩ, R2=10kΩ, R3=10kΩ, R4=5kΩ, R5=31kΩ, R6=47kΩ, R7=15kΩ</li>
            <li><strong>Capacitors:</strong> C1=C2=C3=1nF, C4=360pF</li>
            <li><strong>Power Supply:</strong> V1 = 5V DC</li>
            <li><strong>Analysis Type:</strong> XY Plot (Phase Portrait)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Circuit Type</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-formula&quot;>
        This is a <strong>chaotic oscillator circuit</strong> that exhibits nonlinear dynamics and produces a strange attractor in phase space.
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-grid&quot;>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col blue&quot;>
            <h3>Phase Portrait (V(y) vs V(x))</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Pattern:</strong> Figure-8 shape (double-scroll attractor)</li>
                <li><strong>Behavior:</strong> Chaotic oscillation with bounded trajectory</li>
                <li><strong>V(x) range:</strong> 0.64V to 0.7V</li>
                <li><strong>V(y) range:</strong> 0.5V to 1.3V</li>
                <li><strong>Trajectory:</strong> Never repeats exactly (sensitive to initial conditions)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col red&quot;>
            <h3>Chaotic Characteristics</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Non-periodic:</strong> Output never repeats the same pattern</li>
                <li><strong>Deterministic:</strong> Governed by circuit equations, not random</li>
                <li><strong>Bounded:</strong> Trajectory stays within finite region</li>
                <li><strong>Strange Attractor:</strong> Complex fractal-like structure</li>
                <li><strong>Sensitive Dependence:</strong> Small changes lead to different trajectories</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card green-border&quot;>
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>This circuit demonstrates <strong>chaotic behavior</strong> through its nonlinear transistor dynamics and feedback network. The XY plot reveals a double-scroll strange attractor, characteristic of chaotic systems. Unlike periodic oscillators, this circuit produces a deterministic but unpredictable output that never exactly repeats. The chaotic oscillation arises from the interaction between the two transistors, the RC network, and the nonlinear characteristics of the transistors operating in their active regions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot; style=&quot;background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;&quot;>
        <h2 style=&quot;color: #16a085;&quot;>Applications of Chaotic Circuits</h2>
        <ul style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>
            <li><strong>Secure Communications:</strong> Chaos-based encryption</li>
            <li><strong>Random Number Generation:</strong> True hardware randomness</li>
            <li><strong>Spread Spectrum:</strong> Chaotic signal modulation</li>
            <li><strong>Neural Networks:</strong> Chaotic neuron models</li>
            <li><strong>Testing:</strong> Complex signal generation for system testing</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div>"><div class="ch">
    
    <h1>Chaotic Oscillator Circuit - SPICE Time Domain Analysis</h1>

    <div class="ch-card">
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Transistors (Q1, Q2):</strong> BC549C NPN</li>
            <li><strong>Resistors:</strong> R1=5kΩ, R2=10kΩ, R3=10kΩ, R4=5kΩ, R5=31kΩ, R6=47kΩ, R7=15kΩ</li>
            <li><strong>Capacitors:</strong> C1=C2=C3=1nF, C4=360pF</li>
            <li><strong>Power Supply:</strong> V1 = 5V DC</li>
            <li><strong>Analysis Type:</strong> XY Plot (Phase Portrait)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Circuit Type</h2>
    <div class="ch-formula">
        This is a <strong>chaotic oscillator circuit</strong> that exhibits nonlinear dynamics and produces a strange attractor in phase space.
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class="ch-grid">

        <div class="ch-col blue">
            <h3>Phase Portrait (V(y) vs V(x))</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Pattern:</strong> Figure-8 shape (double-scroll attractor)</li>
                <li><strong>Behavior:</strong> Chaotic oscillation with bounded trajectory</li>
                <li><strong>V(x) range:</strong> 0.64V to 0.7V</li>
                <li><strong>V(y) range:</strong> 0.5V to 1.3V</li>
                <li><strong>Trajectory:</strong> Never repeats exactly (sensitive to initial conditions)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="ch-col red">
            <h3>Chaotic Characteristics</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Non-periodic:</strong> Output never repeats the same pattern</li>
                <li><strong>Deterministic:</strong> Governed by circuit equations, not random</li>
                <li><strong>Bounded:</strong> Trajectory stays within finite region</li>
                <li><strong>Strange Attractor:</strong> Complex fractal-like structure</li>
                <li><strong>Sensitive Dependence:</strong> Small changes lead to different trajectories</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="ch-card green-border">
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">This circuit demonstrates <strong>chaotic behavior</strong> through its nonlinear transistor dynamics and feedback network. The XY plot reveals a double-scroll strange attractor, characteristic of chaotic systems. Unlike periodic oscillators, this circuit produces a deterministic but unpredictable output that never exactly repeats. The chaotic oscillation arises from the interaction between the two transistors, the RC network, and the nonlinear characteristics of the transistors operating in their active regions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ch-card" style="background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;">
        <h2 style="color: #16a085;">Applications of Chaotic Circuits</h2>
        <ul style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">
            <li><strong>Secure Communications:</strong> Chaos-based encryption</li>
            <li><strong>Random Number Generation:</strong> True hardware randomness</li>
            <li><strong>Spread Spectrum:</strong> Chaotic signal modulation</li>
            <li><strong>Neural Networks:</strong> Chaotic neuron models</li>
            <li><strong>Testing:</strong> Complex signal generation for system testing</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div></div></foreignObject></g>